<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain why discounted cash flow techniques provide better criteria for project selection than net profit or return on investment. Highlight on the applicability of IRR with respect to NPV. How can it be calculated manually?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) techniques offer a better criteria for project selection compared to net profit or return on investment (ROI) for several reasons:<br />
1. Time Value of Money: DCF techniques take into account the time value of money, acknowledging that a dollar today is worth more than a dollar in the future. This is crucial for accurately assessing long-term projects.<br />
2. Comprehensive Cash Flow Consideration: Unlike net profit or ROI, which often focus on earnings or profitability, DCF methods consider all cash flows associated with a project,<br />
including initial outlays, ongoing expenses, and final revenue streams.<br />
3. Risk Assessment: DCF methods can incorporate risk assessments by adjusting the discount rate, providing a more realistic view of the project&#8217;s potential.<br />
4. Objective Valuation: DCF methods provide a more objective basis for comparison between<br />
projects, as they are based on projected cash flows rather than accounting profits, which can be subject to different accounting practices. IRR is the discount rate at which the NPV of all cash flows from a project equals zero. It&#8217;s often used to determine the profitability of potential investments. NPV calculates the present value of the project&#8217;s cash flows by discounting them at a predetermined rate, typically the cost of capital.<br />
IRR and NPV:<br />
&#8211; Consistency with Value Maximization: NPV is generally considered superior for making investment decisions as it directly measures the value added to the firm. A project with a positive NPV increases the firm&#8217;s value.<br />
&#8211; Reinvestment Assumption: IRR assumes that the cash flows can be reinvested at the IRR, which might be unrealistically high. NPV uses a more conservative approach, assuming reinvestment at the firm&#8217;s cost of capital.<br />
&#8211; Multiple IRRs and No IRR Issues: In projects with alternating cash flows, IRR can be misleading or impossible to calculate, whereas NPV does not have this issue. Calculating IRR manually involves a trial-and-error method, as it requires solving the equation<br />
where the NPV equals zero. This can be done by:<br />
1. Estimating an initial rate of return and calculating the NPV.<br />
2. Adjusting the rate and recalculating the NPV until it is as close to zero as possible.<br />
3. The IRR is the rate at which this condition is met.<br />
This process can be quite complex and is more efficiently done with financial calculators or spreadsheet software, but it&#8217;s still possible to do it manually if necessary.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>List techniques that are used for progress visualization and explain them. Why do you think project monitoring and control is very challenging?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>After the collection of data by the manager about project progress, he/she needs some way of representing that data to greatest effect. Following are some of the methods for visualizing progress of a project:</p>
<p>i. Gantt chart: It is one of the oldest and simplest technique for tracking project progress. It is an activity bar chart indicating scheduled activity dates.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-29186" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Screenshot-2024-01-16-170214.png?resize=522%2C271&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="522" height="271"></p>
<p>ii. Slip chart: Slip chart provides more visual indication of those activities that are not progressing to schedule. The more slip line bends, grater the validation from the plan.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-29188" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Screenshot-2024-01-16-170407.png?resize=521%2C274&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="521" height="274"></p>
<p>iii. Ball charts: Ball charts are even more striking way of showing whether or not the targets have met. Circles only contains two dates: The original and most recent target dates or the original and actual dates.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-29189" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Screenshot-2024-01-16-170625.png?resize=321%2C222&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="321" height="222"></p>
<p>Project monitoring and control can be challenging due to several reasons:<br />
1. Rapid Technological Changes: The technology evolves rapidly, with frequent updates in tools, platforms, and languages. Keeping a project aligned with the latest technologies while<br />
maintaining progress can be challenging.<br />
2. Human Factor: Software development is highly dependent on the skills, experience, and<br />
collaboration of the development team. Team dynamics, communication issues, or turnover can significantly impact the project&#8217;s progress.<br />
3. Quality Assurance: Ensuring the software meets quality standards and is free of bugs requires thorough testing, which can be time-consuming and difficult to plan accurately. Balancing quality with timely delivery is often one of the most challenging aspects of software project management.<br />
4. User Acceptance: The success of software often depends on user acceptance, which can be<br />
difficult to predict. Monitoring and adjusting the project to align with user feedback requires flexibility and can complicate project timelines</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
