<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What are different stages required to create a project schedule?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The primary stages required to create a project schedule:<br />
1. Define Project Scope: Before you can schedule anything, you need to have a clear understanding of the project&#8217;s scope. This involves defining the project goals, deliverables, tasks, and boundaries.<br />
2. Identify Activities and Tasks: Break down the project into smaller, manageable activities and tasks. This process, known as Work Breakdown Structure (WBS), involves listing out everything that needs to be done to complete the project.<br />
3. Sequence Activities: Determine the order in which the tasks need to be completed. This involves identifying dependencies between tasks, such as which tasks must be completed before others can start (sequential dependencies), and which tasks can be done in parallel.<br />
4. Estimate Resources and Durations: For each task, estimate the resources (labor, equipment, materials) required and the duration it will take to complete. This estimation should be as accurate as possible and can be based on historical data, expert opinions, or standardized formulas.<br />
5. Assign Resources: Allocate the necessary resources to each task. This includes assigning team members to tasks, scheduling the use of equipment, and planning<br />
for material availability.<br />
6. Develop the Schedule: Using the information gathered, start creating the schedule. This is often done using project management software which can help in visualizing the schedule (e.g., Gantt charts), identifying critical paths, and making adjustments as needed.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain project management cycle.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Project Management Life Cycle</p>
<p>It has four phases: each with specific activities and deliverables.</p>
<p>1. Project Initiation</p>
<p>In this phase, the project is defined at a broad level. The project&#8217;s purpose, scope, feasibility, and objectives are identified. The key activities are: Project charter development, stakeholder identification, preliminary cost and timeline estimates.</p>
<p>2.Project Planning</p>
<p>This phase involves detailed planning to establish the project scope, define objectives, outline tasks, and develop schedules and budgets. The key activities are: Work breakdown structure (WBS), resource planning, risk management, scheduling, budgeting, and communication planning.</p>
<p>3. Project Execution</p>
<p>This is the phase where the project plan is put into motion. Resources are allocated, teams are informed, and tasks are performed. The key activities are: Team collaboration, task execution, status meetings, quality assurance, and ongoing communication.</p>
<p>4.Project Closure</p>
<p>Here we formally close the project, ensuring that all objectives are met and stakeholders are satisfied.</p>
<p>We evaluate the project performance and document everything about the project.</p>
<p>We provide the project outputs to the client or end users.</p>
</div>
