<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Highlight on different types of leadership styles.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Leadership style refers to the manner and approach of providing direction, implementing plans, and motivating people. Different leadership styles are suited to different contexts and individuals, and understanding these styles can help leaders become more effective<br />
1. Task-Oriented Leadership (Focus on Work in Hand):<br />
&#8211; This style emphasizes the tasks &amp; jobs that need to be done. Leaders who adopt this approach focus primarily on getting the job done &amp; can be very directive in their management style.<br />
&#8211; Task-oriented leaders typically define the work &amp; roles required, put structures in place, plan, organize, and monitor work closely. They are often less concerned about the well-being of team members, prioritizing efficiency and productivity above all else.<br />
2. People-Oriented Leadership (Focus on Relationships in Uncertain Situations):<br />
-This style is more focused on the relationships within the team. Leaders adopting this style are supportive, and they prioritize the welfare and needs of the members of their team.<br />
&#8211; People-oriented leaders work on building trust and respect, and creating a positive team<br />
atmosphere. They encourage participation, collaboration, and are often good listeners.<br />
3. Reduce Uncertainty (Focus on People-Oriented Tasks):<br />
&#8211; This style combines elements of both task-oriented and people-oriented leadership, focusing<br />
on reducing uncertainty in the team. Leaders adopting this style aim to clarify the path forward,<br />
often by providing structure and support simultaneously.<br />
&#8211; These leaders are proactive in identifying &amp; addressing areas of uncertainty and ambiguity.<br />
They provide clear directions &amp; expectations while also being attentive to team members&#8217; needs and concerns. They often engage in constant communication, offering both guidance &amp; support.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Differentiate between verification and validation. List testing principles.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 288px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">Verification</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">Validation</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">Verification process includes checking documents, design, code, and program.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">Validation process includes testing and validation of the  actual product.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">It does not require executing the code.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">It require executing the code to test the usability and functionality of the product.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">It uses methods like reviews, walkthroughs, inspections, and desk-checking.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">It uses methods like Black box testing, white box testing, and non-functional testing.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">The quality assurance (QA) team would be engaged.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 48px;">The software testing team along with the QA team would be engaged.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 72px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 72px;">It targets internal aspects such as requirements, design, software architecture, database, and code.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 72px;">It targets the end product that is ready to be deployed.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">It comes before validation.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">It comes after verification.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Testing Principles:</p>
<p>1.  All tests should be tractable to customers requirements.</p>
<p>2. Tests should be planned long before testing begins.</p>
<p>3. Testing should begin &#8221; in the small&#8221; and progress toward testing &#8221; in the large&#8221;.</p>
<p>4. 80% of all errors uncovered during testing will likely be tractable to 20% of all program components. That&#8217;s why testing should be done throughly.</p>
<p>5. Testing should be done early to minimize errors.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>What is a baseline? Why Software Configuration Management is a critical activity?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A baseline refers to a defined reference point in the project&#8217;s lifecycle. This reference point serves as a standard or benchmark against which actual performance and progress can be measured. Baselines are established for various aspects of a project, including scope, cost, schedule, and quality. The purpose of establishing a baseline is to provide a stable basis for<br />
assessing project performance and managing changes. Software Configuration Management (SCM) is a critical activity in the software development process due to its role in efficiently managing and controlling changes in the software. SCM<br />
addresses the complexities of software development by ensuring that changes are made systematically and that the integrity and consistency of the software product are maintained over time. Some aspects of it are:<br />
1. Managing Changes: Software projects are dynamic, often requiring changes in code, design, and other documents. SCM helps in tracking and controlling these changes, ensuring that they are made without disrupting the project&#8217;s progress.<br />
2. Version Control: SCM involves version control, which is crucial for maintaining different versions of software products. It allows teams to manage multiple versions, revert to previous versions if necessary, and understand the evolution of the software over time.<br />
3. Coordination Among Team Members: In a team environment, multiple developers work on different parts of the same software. SCM ensures that changes made by different team members are integrated smoothly, reducing the chances of conflicts or overwrites in the codebase.<br />
4. Maintaining Consistency and Integrity: SCM maintains the consistency &amp; integrity of the software by ensuring that all components (code, documentation, tests, etc.) are synchronized &amp; updated. This is especially important in complex projects with many dependencies.<br />
5. Facilitates Build and Release Management: SCM supports the build and release management process by keeping track of which versions of which components make up a given build or release. This is essential for efficient deployment and troubleshooting</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Why PERT chart is an efficient technique? Explain estimated time, standard deviation and Z-value with respect to PERT chart.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The Program Evaluation and Review Technique (PERT) chart is considered an efficient technique for project management due to its unique approach in handling uncertainties and complexities in project timelines. PERT charts are particularly useful in planning, scheduling, and coordinating tasks within large and complex projects. Here&#8217;s why PERT charts are efficient:<br />
1. Handling Uncertainty: PERT involves estimating the shortest (optimistic), longest (pessimistic), and most likely durations for each task. This range of time estimates helps in dealing with uncertainty in project planning and execution.<br />
2. Visual Representation: A PERT chart provides a visual representation of a project’s timeline by illustrating the tasks, their durations, and dependencies. This helps in identifying critical paths and potential bottlenecks.<br />
3. Focus on Critical Path: By highlighting the critical path, PERT charts help project managers to focus on tasks that directly impact the project timeline, enabling more effective allocation of resources and attention.<br />
4. Flexibility in Planning: PERT charts allow for adjustments and updates as more information becomes available or as conditions change, making them adaptable to dynamic project environments.</p>
<p>Estimated Time: In PERT, the estimated time for each task is calculated using the formula: E = (O + 4M + P) / 6 ,Where E is the estimated time, O is the optimistic time, M is the most likely time, and P is the pessimistic time.</p>
<p>Standard Deviation: The standard deviation in PERT is used to measure the uncertainty or variability of the time estimate. It is calculated as: SD = (P &#8211; O) / 6 This formula gives an idea of how spread out the times are over the range from optimistic to pessimistic. A higher standard deviation indicates greater uncertainty in the time estimates.</p>
<p>Z-value (or Z-score): The Z-value in the context of PERT is used to assess the probability of completing the project within a certain time frame. It is calculated by comparing the desired project completion time (DCT) with the expected project completion time (EPT) and the standard deviation of the project’s critical path. The formula is: Z = (DCT &#8211; EPT) / (Standard Deviation of Critical Path) The Z-value can then be used to find the probability of completing the project on or before the desired time by referencing a standard normal distribution table</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Short Notes:</p>
<p>a) Annual Worth</p>
<p>b) Risk Exposure</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>a) Annual Worth<br />
The annual worth of a project is a financial measure used to evaluate the average annual economic impact of a project over its lifespan. It converts all of the project&#8217;s cash flows, including initial investment, ongoing operational costs, and revenues, into a uniform annual<br />
value. This is accomplished by first identifying the project&#8217;s cash inflows and outflows and then discounting these amounts to their present value using a chosen discount rate, typically the cost of capital or desired rate of return. The concept is based on the time value of money, acknowledging that money available now is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its potential earning capacity. The annual worth calculation helps in comparing the economic viability of different projects, particularly when they have differing life spans and cash flow structures. A positive annual worth indicates a profitable project, while a negative value suggests it may not be financially viable. This uniform annual figure simplifies complex financial assessments by providing a consistent basis for<br />
comparison, making it a valuable tool in capital budgeting and investment decision-making.</p>
<p>b) Risk Exposure<br />
Risk exposure management refers to the potential impact of risks on the project, considering both the likelihood of the risk occurring and the severity of its consequences. It&#8217;s a measure of the extent to which a project is threatened by a potential risk. Understanding risk exposure is crucial for effective risk management, as it helps project managers prioritize risks and develop strategies to mitigate them.<br />
Risk exposure is typically calculated by multiplying the probability of a risk occurring by the impact of that risk:<br />
Risk Exposure = Probability of Occurrence ×Impact<br />
For example, if there&#8217;s a 40% chance of a critical software component failing (probability), which would lead to a two-month delay and Rs.100,000 in extra costs (impact), the risk exposure could be calculated in monetary terms</p>
